<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-03-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-03-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="73" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d73">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 493.11/490.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                Minister <persName type="to">Reinsch</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-03-16">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 16, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Treasury Department reports that Chinese Government paid in January last
                            in round numbers $90,000 on account of the January 1914 quota of the
                            Boxer Indemnity, which payment was made before reverting to the 1909
                            method of effecting payments and remissions at Shanghai. The amount to
                            be retained by the United States being about $45,000, there remains
                            about an equal sum to be refunded to China.</p>
                        <p>You will inquire of the Foreign Office whether this Government is to pay
                            the remitted portion to the Chinese Legation here, as was done on
                            January 31 last, for the support of indemnity students in the United
                            States.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>